Test-Driven Development is a way to do Unit Testing.Unit Testing is LOW LEVEL tests for individual "units" of code - Units are usually a method on a class - Each test exercises that "unit" in isolation from it's dependencies - ONE UNIT at a time. - You cannot write a unit test that: - touches the network - uses a database - writes to or reads from the file system - depends on the clock - no "external attached resources" - Code that has a different rate of change from the code you are testing.FSDBTest-Driven-Development - a design "form" - a style we adopt to do our work for a purpose. - You don't need to nor should you do this all the time. - Use TDD especially when you are figuring out new things.Form:RedGreenRefactorCommit1. Start with a meaningfully failing test.2. Get it to pass as quickly as possible. - Time box this. - Write crappy code. Really. 3.
